05118nam a22007695i 9780231538640DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20152015nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2014013368  a97802315386407 a10.7312/nola167042doi  a(DE-B1597)458451  a(OCoLC)979904304  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aPQ3897b.N65 2015 7aLCO0070002bisacsh04a840.98962231 aNoland, Carrie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aVoices of Negritude in Modernist Print :bAesthetic Subjectivity, Diaspora, and the Lyric Regime /cCarrie Noland. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (344 p.) :b6 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aModernist Latitudes00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. “Seeing with the Eyes of the Work” (Adorno): Césaire’s Cahier and Modernist Print Culture -- t2. The Empirical Subject in Question: A Drama of Voices in Aimé Césaire’s Et les chiens se taisaient -- t3. Poetry and the Typosphere in Léon-Gontran Damas -- t4. Léon-Gontran Damas: Writing Rhythm in the Interwar Period -- t5. Red Front / Black Front: Aimé Césaire and the Affaire Aragon -- t6. To Inhabit a Wound: A Turn to Language in Martinique -- tConclusion -- tAppendix 1. English Translation of Léon-Gontran Damas’s “Hoquet” -- tAppendix 2. English Translation of Aimé Césaire’s “Calendrier lagunaire” -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCarrie Noland approaches Negritude as an experimental, text-based poetic movement developed by diasporic authors of African descent through the means of modernist print culture. Engaging primarily the works of Aimé Césaire and Léon-Gontran Damas, Noland shows how the demands of print culture alter the personal voice of each author, transforming an empirical subjectivity into a hybrid, textual entity that she names, after Theodor Adorno, an "aesthetic subjectivity." This aesthetic subjectivity, transmitted by the words on the page, must be actualized—performed, reiterated, and created anew—by each reader, at each occasion of reading. Lyric writing and lyric reading therefore attenuate the link between author and phenomenalized voice. Yet the Negritude poem insists upon its connection to lived experience even as it emphasizes its printed form. Ironically, a purely formalist reading would have to ignore the ways formal—and not merely thematic—elements point toward the poem's own conditions of emergence. Blending archival research on the historical context of Negritude with theories of the lyric "voice," Noland argues that Negritude poems present a challenge to both form-based (deconstructive) theories and identity-based theories of poetic representation. Through close readings, she reveals that the racialization of the author places pressure on a lyric regime of interpretation, obliging us to reconceptualize the relation of author to text in poetries of the first person.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAfrican diaspora in literature. 0aBlacks in literature. 0aBook industries and tradezFrancexHistoryy20th century. 0aFrench poetryxBlack authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aFrench poetryzForeign countriesxHistory and criticism. 0aLiteraturexAesthetics. 0aModernism (Aesthetics)zFrance. 0aNegritude (Literary movement) 0aNegritude (Literary movement). 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / Caribbean & Latin American.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066586440uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/nola1670440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231538640423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/97